      "id":"film/2013/oct/06/ac-lyles",
      "sectionId":"film",
      "sectionName":"Film",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-06T15:58:56Z",
      "webTitle":"AC Lyles obituary",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/oct/06/ac-lyles",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2013/oct/06/ac-lyles",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"30",
        "trailText":"Veteran film producer and friend to many  of Hollywood's stars",
        "headline":"AC Lyles obituary",
        "body":"<p>The office walls of the film producer AC Lyles, who has died aged 95, were plastered with celebrity photographs. He seemed to know everybody in Hollywood, from presidents and governors to the great names of film, such as Elizabeth Taylor, Bob Hope and Bing Crosby. James Cagney, William Holden and Ronald Reagan were close personal friends.</p><p>Lyles worked for the same company, Paramount, for most of his life, starting as a mailroom office boy in 1937, after the studio's head, Adolph Zukor, gave in to his weekly letters begging for a job.</p><p>Indeed, he maintained that he had decided on his ninth birthday that he was going to be a producer. At the age of 10, he had a cleaning job at the Paramount cinema in his home town of Jacksonville, Florida, and seeing the silent film Wings, starring Clara Bow, reinforced this aspiration. When he was 14, he interviewed visiting stars for the Jacksonville Journal, his local paper, always concentrating on those with Paramount contracts. When Zukor came to the theatre, it was the chance he had been waiting for. The mogul told him to \"keep in touch\", and once he had left school, Lyles set off for Los Angeles.</p><p>In 1939, he became director of the studio's publicity department, one of the most crucial jobs in the film industry. Working on publicity for B-movies brought him into contact with the \"Dollar Bills\" – Bill Pine and Bill Thomas – renowned for economical film-making. Lyles in turn convinced the studio that he could work in this vein, using his contacts with well-established stars and squeezing budgets as necessary.</p><p>After he had assisted the producer of The Mountain (1956), a climbing drama with Spencer Tracy and Robert Wagner, Cagney asked him to produce the only film that the gangster actor ever directed, Short Cut to Hell (1957). Lyles recalled some time later: \"I don't think he liked telling actors what to do.\"</p><p>Among the pictures that Lyles went on to produce, Hostile Guns (1967) and Buckskin (1968) were much to the familiar western pattern of the good guys in white hats, helped by the honest sheriff, chasing the baddies out of town. He had his own production company – working, of course, under the Paramount banner – with titles such as The Young and the Brave (1963), Law of The Lawless (1964) and Red Tomahawk (1967).</p><p>For a time he worked in television, with a number of celebrated series to his credit. On loan to CBS, he produced the mammoth hit Rawhide (1959), which starred the young Clint Eastwood. His final credit came in his 80s as consulting producer on another western series, the HBO success Deadwood (2005-06).</p><p>Lyles has a star on Hollywood Boulevard's Walk of Fame and in recent years continued his work for Paramount as a goodwill ambassador; he also headed a number of charities. He had encouraged Reagan at the start of his political career, when he was seeking election as governor of California. Once the former actor had become president, he appointed Lyles to his advisory committee on private sector initiatives, and unofficially made him the man to arrange stars' visits to the White House.</p><p>The well turned-out and friendly Lyles would have made a good president himself – or at least would have been well-cast acting one. But that was not for him. \"I never wanted to act,\" he said. \"Not even a walk-on in the pictures that I made.\" However, he did appear in various TV documentaries.</p><p>In 1948, Lyles married the actor <a href=\"http://www.glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen.com/show.php?id=278\" title=\"Martha Vickers profile\">Martha Vickers</a>, but they divorced the following year. In 1955, he married Martha French and she survives him.</p><p>• Andrew Craddock Lyles, film producer, born 17 May 1918; died 27 September 2013</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419187775|2013-10-07T10:05:55Z|97f40f292c8d94ace1e09aed88cfddd337836e52 -->",
