      "id":"film/2013/oct/06/british-film-the-last-passenger",
      "sectionId":"film",
      "sectionName":"Film",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-05T23:05:48Z",
      "webTitle":"Suspense, trains, brand new special effects: the return of the British action thriller",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/oct/06/british-film-the-last-passenger",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2013/oct/06/british-film-the-last-passenger",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"11",
        "trailText":"Vintage rolling stock and a touch of the old Hitchcockian drama play their part in a riposte to Hollywood",
        "headline":"Suspense, trains, brand new special effects: the return of the British action thriller",
        "body":"<p>From the warm waters of <em>Pirates of the Caribbean</em> to the fairytale castle in <em>Snow White and the Huntsman</em>, British film studios now regularly create exotic sets for blockbusters. Last year, however, the largest production space at Shepperton, called the &quot;H-Stage&quot;, was dominated by the more mundane hulks of two reclaimed British railway carriages, dating from the slam-door days.</p><p>The battered train is the unlikely focus of an attempt to bring back the action thriller to this country. <em>Last Passenger</em>, which stars Dougray Scott and opens in cinemas next week, is the debut feature from director Omid Nooshin, a former art student from Guildford, Surrey, who aims to reclaim Britain's reputation for Hitchcockian suspense and couple it with special effects that rival Hollywood.</p><p>&quot;British film-makers love spectacle and adventure, but that doesn't mean they necessarily get to make those movies,&quot; said Nooshin.</p><p>On set last year, Scott was asked to repeatedly leap free of the gas flame burners that surrounded the carriages as Nooshin filmed his character's attempts to save the other passengers. Playing the part of a doctor and single father trapped on what should have been a normal train journey home from London, Scott was clearly enjoying the opportunity to bring terror to the screen.</p><p>&quot;I don't see why we shouldn't make as exciting films here, if not better, than they do in America,&quot; the star told the <em>Observer</em> after a morning's shooting. &quot;We have a different tone, grittier perhaps, but that can make it more real.&quot;</p><p>It all became too real during the shooting of the final sequence of the film, as the train falls apart. &quot;Our train caught fire during one take and we had to evacuate while the fire was extinguished,&quot; said Nooshin. &quot;It was good to get out in the daylight. By that point we'd been cooped up on the train for nearly five weeks, and more than a few of us were going stir crazy.&quot;</p><p>The old rolling stock used was hunted down on the internet and found in a field in Wales. It provides the location for the whole film, the story of an attempt to kidnap a train and send it hurtling to its doom.</p><p>The director, who wrote the screenplay with Andy Love, had the idea sitting on a train alone one night. His first task was to convince his producers and potential backers that with clever technology the right impact could be created without a large special effects team. He did this by making a &pound;500 trailer, filming it in a few hours with a heritage train on loan from the Bluebell Railway in Sussex. On the strength of this footage, Path&eacute; and then the British Film Institute and Pinewood Studios, the owner of Shepperton, stepped forward with some finance.</p><p>Working with 90&nbsp;tonnes of train supported on a hydraulic cradle was not easy. Nooshin admits he thought the project was in trouble &quot;all the time&quot;, particularly on the first day of principal photography. &quot;That's when the magnitude of what you're up against hits you hardest, when you have to dig deep to push on through. We were making <em>Last Passenger</em> for a fraction of the budget of similar movies, so time and resources were often stretched to breaking point. It forces you to be tenacious,&quot; he said.</p><p>Scott, his director believes, makes a perfect Hitchcockian hero: &quot;American action stars tend to play cool under pressure. Everyone knows the shot of the badass hero strolling nonchalantly away from an explosion without turning around. That trope is emblematic of a fantasy bravado. And while Dougray certainly has a self-assured masculinity, it's coupled with an underlying vulnerability which makes him more relatable,&quot; he said.</p><p>Hitchcock got us to care about his heroes by making sure they had some emotional or even physical issues, like Jimmy Stewart's broken leg in <em>Rear Window</em>. &quot;Dougray is strong on the outside but partly broken on the inside, so it's not a foregone conclusion he will save the day,&quot; said Nooshin.</p><p>Scott co-stars with Kara Tointon, the former <em>EastEnders</em> actress and one-time winner of <em>Strictly Come Dancing</em>, but neither of them could have made their dilemma convincing without a new kind of rear projection technique invented for use on the film, much cheaper than the &quot;green screening&quot; that is the custom in Hollywood. Six screens allowed a 360-degree perspective that maintains the impression of movement outside the train windows.</p><p>&quot;When you're making a sci-fi or fantasy, the audience cut you more slack because they know intuitively what they're watching is fabricated, and have no personal frame of reference for that world. But everyone has ridden a train, so you better ensure the illusion is flawless,&quot; said Nooshin, who is now working on a sci-fi production.</p><p>Will audiences buy into his different, British kind of action thriller? Nooshin said that for him the appeal was putting personal experience, rather than screen cliches, into his plot. &quot;Taking those elements and throwing them into the kind of scenario usually associated with Hollywood was entertaining to me, but I guess it's for others to say how British the tone is,&quot; he said.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419119254|2013-10-07T10:05:55Z|9c733ca409d2f7d99e07f58d57a1f27d74c44fed -->",
