      "id":"film/2013/oct/06/guy-lodge-dvds-bfi-player",
      "sectionId":"film",
      "sectionName":"Film",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-05T23:05:33Z",
      "webTitle":"Guy Lodge's DVDs and downloads",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/oct/06/guy-lodge-dvds-bfi-player",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2013/oct/06/guy-lodge-dvds-bfi-player",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"24",
        "trailText":"<p>Britain's biggest film archive is online, free and open for business, writes <strong>Guy Lodge</strong></p>",
        "headline":"Guy Lodge's DVDs and downloads",
        "body":"<video data-media-id=\"gu-video-417109436\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"\">\n        <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2013/9/12/130911SelfishGiant-16x9.mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/connectedTV/1280/2013/9/12/130911SelfishGiant-720.mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/9/12/130911SelfishGiant_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2013/9/12/130911SelfishGiant_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/640/2013/9/12/130911SelfishGiant_vpx.webm\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/ad/2013/9/12/130911SelfishGiant/130911SelfishGiant.m3u8\"></source>\n      </video><p>With autumn fully in swing and the couch an increasingly appealing entertainment venue, it seems appropriate to lead with this week's best streaming-related news: the long-awaited introduction of the British Film Institute's on-demand service. <a href=\"http://www.bfi.org.uk/bfi-player\" title=\"\"><strong>BFI Player</strong></a><strong>  </strong>launches on Wednesday with seven \"collections\" offering more than 1,000 viewing items between them. Much of the content will tie in to the <a href=\"http://www.bfi.org.uk/lff\" title=\"\">London film festival</a> and the BFI's current <a href=\"http://www.bfi.org.uk/gothic\" title=\"\">gothic</a> season, though it's also a welcome outlet for the greatest film archive in Britain.</p><p>One channel will be devoted to the collected works of Edwardian documentary trailblazers <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitchell_and_Kenyon\" title=\"\">Mitchell and Kenyon</a>; another to selections from <em>Sight &amp; Sound</em>'s <a href=\"http://www.bfi.org.uk/news/50-greatest-films-all-time\" title=\"\">greatest films of all-time poll</a>. New releases will also be streamed, beginning later this month with Clio Barnard's magnificent northern fable <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155239/selfish-giant\" title=\"\"><em>The Selfish Giant</em></a>. Most exciting of all, about 60% of the BFI Player's content will be free to view – I expect we'll be returning to this goldmine frequently in the future.</p><p>In the same year that geek god Joss Whedon (last responsible for Marvel's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/144027/avengers\" title=\"\"><em>The Avengers</em></a>) brought out his modern-dress version of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=reYclxg3kts\" title=\"\"><strong>Much Ado About Nothing</strong></a><em> </em>(Kaleidoscope, 12), shot on the fly in his own Californian manse, James Earl Jones and Vanessa Redgrave have been pilloried by London's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/sep/22/much-ado-midsummer-herd-review\" title=\"\">theatre critics</a> for their geriatric take on the Bard's eternally youthful romcom.</p><p>If Whedon fares a little better it's because his ensemble – gathered from his own loquacious TV shows, lending the impression of tightly knit theatre company with a sideline in shampoo ads – have the requisite verbal snap and agility for the material. There's not a Redgrave in the bunch, but that's beside the point. This is <em>Much Ado</em> as snark-era sitcom, scarcely disguised by the scrappy black-and-white photography – which is flattered by a smaller screen. Many loved it; I found it as smug and throwaway in tone as all Whedon's work.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-419112999'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/10/4/1380886542752/Bachelorette-001.jpg' alt='Bachelorette' width='220' height='220' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Kirsten Dunst in the 'scabrously funny' Bachelorette. Photograph: Allstar</figcaption></figure><p>Two of the week's most enjoyable DVD releases sound distinctly unappealing on paper. <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jS0St2NMk1Q\" title=\"\"><strong>Come As You Are</strong></a><strong>&nbsp;</strong>(Eureka, 15) is a road-trip comedy in which three young special needs men head to Spain to lose their virginity; you might be grimacing already, but there's a sincere sweetness and warm sense of community to the trio's antics. You only hope they don't run into the three toxic antiheroines of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w2KKLUrVP20\" title=\"\"><strong>Bachelorette</strong></a><strong> </strong>(Lionsgate, 15), a scabrously funny entry in the admittedly overpopulated wed-com genre. Unfairly dismissed as a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/142098/bridesmaids\" title=\"\"><em>Bridesmaids</em></a> cash-in, its study of the crueller side of female friendship cuts wincingly close to the bone, and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/kirsten-dunst\" title=\"\">Kirsten Dunst</a> is tremendous as a critically insecure queen bee.</p><p>American cultural commentators were fixated last week on the finale of <strong> </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/breaking-bad\" title=\"\"><strong>Breaking Bad</strong></a><strong>. </strong>A TV series built on the age-old fusion of cancer drama and Albuquerque methamphetamine production, it's pitched halfway between Tolstoy and Elmore Leonard. If, like me, you're still playing catch-up, you'll be glad to know that every episode is now to be found on <a href=\"https://signup.netflix.com/\">Netflix</a>.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418994849|2013-10-07T10:05:55Z|adbe11981245620c32f3757639b91de6488f4cf5 -->",
