        "headline":"The To Do List – review",
        "body":"<p>Reading this on a mobile? <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UKGigK17eSs\" title=\"\">Click here</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/122746/bucket.list\" title=\"\"><em>The Bucket List</em></a> had two terminally ill old men compiling a list of things to do before they died, but both were lucky enough to peg out without having to suffer this movie.</p><p>It's arguable that there's something empowering about a <em>Porky's</em>-style comedy in which the girls (rather than the guys) are in the driving seat, with star Aubrey Plaza declaring that \"I don't think that I had ever read a script about a girl who is trying to lose her virginity that is realistic and pushes the envelope\".</p><p>Yet writer/director Maggie Carey's clodhopping coming-of-age yarn merely proves that terrible teen movies are now a source of equal-ops embarrassment for both genders. Plaza plays the straight-A student who resolves to work her way through the sexual lexicon, with hand jobs, blow-jobs, and rim jobs all flagged up to dismally unfunny effect.</p><p>Drawings of foreskins and discussions of lube get a look-in too, as does the sight of parents having inappropriate sex. Eventually (inevitably?) someone gets to eat a poo. Who says comedy is dead?</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418878425|2013-10-07T10:05:55Z|8c159195b434f5cbb8afb0ed8b6d4d4e75817959 -->",
